<TITLE> Banks drive stocks higher </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Dec 17 (bdnews24.com)  Stocks ended higher Monday after a long weekend with banks dominating the trading. Trading was suspended Sunday as the nation observed Victory Day. "The bourse has seen bank-led recovery. Banks are favourable to investors on reports the UCBL will hold pending AGMs," said market analyst Yawer Sayeed, also chief executive of AIMS of Bangladesh. "However, the investors may opt for bank shares on expectations of higher prices at the beginning of the next year. It also is the closing time of the year for banks," said Sayeed, who manages AIMS 1st mutual fund and Grameen 1 MF. The Dhaka Stock Exchange on the first trading day of the week opened with a rise in the general index before declining in the third hour of trading. It however recovered losses and gained in the midday session and remained relatively steady towards the end. The DGEN or general index closed at 2965.57, up 29.40 points or 1.00 percent. The DSI or all share price index rose 25.11 points or 1.01 percent to 2500.03. The DSE-20 blue chip index also edged up 8.54 points, or 0.36 percent, to close at 2350.54. Turnover increased to Tk 1.21 billion from Thursday's Tk 1.08 billion from trading of 4,308,852 shares. Gainers beat losers 108 to 91 and 20 issues remained unchanged. BRAC Bank was at the peak of the top share board by value. It gained from the previous trading, closing at Tk 1634, up 4.25 percent. UCBL followed BRAC Bank, rising 2.65 percent to Tk 4592.75. Prime Bank edged up 2.73 percent to end at Tk 863.50. NBL, however, lost after gaining the previous day. It dipped 1.01 percent to close at Tk 1363.25. Shahjalal Bank gained 3.97 percent to Tk 366. Among the other scrips on the top share board by value, South East Bank, Uttara Bank Power Grid Company of Bangladesh and Standard Bank gained. Islami Bank Perpetual Bond slipped. Aziz Pipes, Paper Processing, 8th ICB Mutual Fund, Daffodil Computers and Dutch Bangla Bank topped the gainers. Modern Cement, Excelsior Shoes, Gulf Foods, Tripti Industries and BOC Bangladesh were among the major losers. All the indices on the Chittagong Stock Exchange also ended higher. The CSCX or selective categories index closed 49.75 points or 1.04 percent up at 4832.68. The CASPI or all share price index ended at 7547.71, up 79.77 points or 1.06 percent. The CSE-30 blue chip also rose to 6672.79, up 77.55 points or 1.17 percent. Turnover on the bourse however declined to Tk 177.951 million from Thursday's Tk 181.403 million. Of the issues traded, 57 advanced, 32 declined and 12 held steady. bd
